node.text:
May the sun guide your way through the many layers of life. 
•••••
Thanks to Julianna @julitmart for the beautiful view. 
•
...goodbye summer...ok, I know that we have a couple more weeks of summer left - but with schools starting again (and a husband who is a professor) - it always feels to me like Labor Day weekend is the end of summer...

One thing that I have enjoyed over the last year and a half is exploring some regions of the East Coast more in depth. We had to cancel 2 major trips because of the pandemic. But I enjoyed our alternate plans in places like the New River Gorge (even  before it was a National Park 😊 ) and Charleston 🌴. My husband and I spent 4 years in NC in our 20s ( post-doc years) and we had loved going into the mountains. I have thoroughly enjoyed the multiple trips I have been to take to that region in the past year and a half - I have fallen in love with those mountains all over again. Actually. I am currently quite obsessed with that region. There is nothing quite like the layers of the the southern Appalachian Mountains ! 🌄

Have a great weekend ! ( photo is from another sunset hike in the NC mountains a few weeks ago).

Photo by National Park Geek® in Glacier National Park with @glaciernps, @glacierconservancy, and @_jeffreyji. May be an image of nature.

node.text:
Some say Mountain Views are the best. Who are we to argue with that. 
•••••
Thanks to Jeffrey @_jeffreyji for the inspiration from Glacier NP. 
•
“In the Wind”
.
Glacier’s landscapes are diverse as they are beautiful. Hiking through the park, you’ll be greeted with jaw dropping views of mountains and valleys below. People often call Glacier a hiker’s paradise and if you day hike through one of the popular trails like highline or Grinnell Glacier, you’ll see why. It’s honestly breath taking to be in that environment, on the trail surrounded by views such as this. 
.
This image was shot on of the hikes, specifically highline. The mountains were just unending through the 11 miles, especially the first half of the hike. Half way through, I saw this scene, with a powerful peak, the lighting was pretty decent mid day light and the foreground had a multitude of bear swaying in the wind. I wanted to capture the granduer of all the mountains in this park using this peak as a symbol and have beargrass in the foreground to show one the plants and the fauna you could encounter in the park. It’s quite dreamy surreal hiking through glacier and it’s one of my favorite parks, my favorite in the US.
——-

node.text:
Forget about the week in a forest full of Sequoia trees. 🌲
••••
Many thanks to Michael @_mcastaneda_ for sharing the beautiful day at Sequoia National Park. 
•
I often wonder how the experience must have been for the first people to walk through new lands like this. The sheer magnitude of these giants had to leave that first wanderer completely awestruck and feeling as if they were in a totally new world. I wonder how the conversation went as they tried to explain to a friend this new and exotic discovery. Were these peoples encounters so much different than my own? Exploring landscapes on this planet brings you head on to some absolutely amazing views and I often struggle in words to explain exactly what I saw and many times am mesmerized while on location by the awesome beauty this planet constantly provides. I picked up a camera to try and express those words through image but even still the experience can't always be captured. To me, my work is more than a representation of what nature has to offer but a beacon that calls out for people to go on adventures of their own.
